stylometry: Transportation problems find the optimal path to ship goods from one node to another.  Transshipment problems find the optimal path to ship goods from one node, to an intermediary (a wharehouse) and then to another node.  Nodes are the starting and ending points in a transportation or transshipment model.  Arcs are the path the information is being sent from one node to another.  Flows are the information that is being sent over the arc.  An example of a transhipment problem would be parts leaving Cleveland, arriving in Chicago and then being sent from Chicago to LA.
